lights\n*   **Data center infrastructure:** 20 - 25 years\n*   **Launch sites:** 7 - 20 years\n*   **Buildings and improvements:** 30 years\n*   **Leasehold improvements:** Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease\n\n### 4. Nature of the AI Segment's Compute Infrastructure Investments\nThe AI segment (formed following the acquisition of xAI in February 2026) is characterized as capital-intensive, early-stage, and focused on long-term growth. The nature of its compute infrastructure investments includes:\n*   **Hardware and Data Centers:** The company is investing heavily in specialized computing hardware, including obtaining third-party GPUs and manufacturing its own GPUs. This also includes constructing, leasing, maintaining, enhancing, and expanding data centers.\n*   **Construction-in-Progress (CIP):** As of March 31, 2026, CIP stood at $14,045 million (up from $4,604 million at year-end 2025), primarily comprising ongoing construction and expansion of facilities and AI infrastructure not yet placed in service. The company also capitalized $7 million in interest in Q1 2026 and $169 million in FY 2025 related to these significant long-term AI data center projects.\n*   **Power and Operational Costs:** AI research and development costs include cloud computing expenses, power generation costs, and depreciation of data center assets (processors, networking equipment). \n*   **Scale and Timeline:** Capital expenditures for AI are scaling as quickly as the company can deploy power and compute to address a $26.5 trillion potential market opportunity. However, the company expects a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA, explicitly warning that prioritizing this long-term growth may result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses.",
