    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial document chunks, here is the relationship between the Connectivity segment\'s capital expenditures (CapEx) and depreciation, and the segment\'s reinvestment needs:\n\n**Relationship Between CapEx and Depreciation**\nAcross all reported periods, the Connectivity segment\'s capital expenditures significantly outpace its depreciation and amortization (D&A). This indicates that the segment is currently in a heavy growth and network expansion phase, rather than just a maintenance phase. \n\n**Need for Continual Reinvestment in Satellite Replacement**\nYes, the Connectivity segment will need to continually reinvest in satellite replacement. The text specifies that the segment operates a broadband network "powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit." The notes detail that "Satellites include costs to build the satellites... as well as capitalized launch costs," and the MD&A highlights "higher depreciation of capitalized launch and satellite costs due to the increase in Starlink flights." Because these satellites are capitalized and depreciated over their useful lives, the company will naturally need to continually launch replacement satellites to maintain its network capacity as the current fleet ages, in addition to the satellites it is launching to expand the network. \n\n**Magnitude of Connectivity CapEx vs. Depreciation**\nThe magnitude of CapEx consistently dwarfs depreciation, showing that the company is investing heavily in future capacity:\n*   **Full Year 2023:** CapEx was $2,455 million compared to D&A of $884 million (CapEx was roughly 2.8x higher).\n*   **Full Year 2024:** CapEx was $3,498 million compared to D&A of $1,508 million (CapEx was roughly 2.3x higher).\n*   **Three Months Ended March 31, 2025:** CapEx was $814 million compared to D&A of $510 million.\n*   **Three Months Ended March 31, 2026:** CapEx was $1,332 million compared to D&A of $783 million. \n\nThe document notes that these year-over-year increases in CapEx are "primarily driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs as we continue to increase our number of satellites and grow our satellite network."',
