2026-06-24 23:46:18,109 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Two Situations Where EBITDA-Based Segment Comparisons Could Materially Misrepresent Economic Profitability\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as segment income (loss) from operations excluding (i) depreciation and amortization, (ii) share-based compensation, (iii) restructuring charges, and (iv) impairment. Because D&A and SBC are stripped out, this measure is highly sensitive to differences in capital intensity, asset useful lives, and the accounting classification of long-lived asset creation across the three reportable segments (Space, Connectivity, AI). Two situations stand out where EBITDA-based segment comparisons could materially misrepresent economic profitability:\n\n---\n\n### Situation 1: Capital-Intensity and Depreciation-Timing Asymmetries Across Segments\n\nThe three segments have radically different capital-intensity profiles and asset useful lives, yet EBITDA excludes depreciation entirely—making cross-segment EBITDA comparisons economically misleading.\n\n**AI segment — depreciation is artificially suppressed today and will be excluded tomorrow.**\n- AI CapEx scaled from $463M (2023) → $5,633M (2024) → $12,727M (2025) → $7,723M in Q1 2026 alone.\n- As of March 31, 2026, total Construction-in-Progress was **$14,045M** (up from $4,604M at YE 2025), which the filing states is "primarily comprised of … AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service." Assets in CIP are **not yet depreciating**, so the AI segment\'s current EBITDA understates the true economic cost of the capital base already deployed. Once placed in service, the resulting depreciation (servers 5–6 yrs; data centers 20–25 yrs) will be **excluded** from Segment Adjusted EBITDA—so the very cost of the AI build-out will never flow through this metric.\n\n**Connectivity segment — short satellite lives and a perpetual replacement cycle are invisible in EBITDA.**\n- Starlink satellites have useful lives of only **3–5 years**, and the company "often deorbits and replaces Starlink satellites before they reach the end of their estimated useful lives." This requires continuous reinvestment merely to maintain constellation density.\n- Connectivity CapEx consistently dwarfs its D&A (e.g., 2024: $3,498M CapEx vs. $1,508M D&A; 2023: $2,455M vs. $884M). EBITDA excludes the depreciation that reflects the real economic consumption of the satellite fleet and ignores the structural reinvestment requirement. A high Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA ($7,168M in 2025) therefore overstates sustainable economic profit because it omits both the depreciation of the existing fleet and the ongoing CapEx needed to replace it.\n\n**Space segment — different depreciation method entirely.**\n- Flight vehicle hardware is depreciated on a **units-of-production basis (5–25 flights)**, not straight-line. This produces a fundamentally different depreciation pattern than the straight-line depreciation used for satellites, servers, and data centers. Adding back D&A is therefore not economically equivalent across segments.\n\n**Net effect:** Comparing AI EBITDA to Connectivity EBITDA, or either to Space, ignores that (a) the AI segment\'s EBITDA is flattered by $14B of CIP not yet depreciating, (b) the Connectivity segment\'s EBITDA ignores a 3–5 year satellite replacement treadmill, and (c) the segments use different depreciation methods. EBITDA-based ranking of segment "profitability" does not reflect the true cost of the capital each segment consumes.\n\n---\n\n### Situation 2: Asymmetric Treatment of Long-Lived Asset Creation (R&D Expensed vs. Capitalized)\n\nThe Space and AI segments are both building long-lived productive assets, but the costs are classified differently—and EBITDA treats those classifications very differently.\n\n**Space — Starship R&D is expensed as incurred and reduces EBITDA.**\n- Because Starship is in the development stage, "a majority of its costs are expensed to R&D as incurred," including test flight hardware, Raptor engines (expensed when used in test flights), employee compensation, tooling, and depreciation of R&D equipment. These costs flow directly through Segment Adjusted EBITDA as a reduction. The filing explicitly attributes the Space segment\'s decline to $(351)M Segment Adjusted EBITDA in Q1 2026 (from $224M in Q1 2025) to "accelerated investment in the development of the Starship vehicle."\n\n**AI — compute infrastructure is capitalized, and the resulting depreciation is excluded from EBITDA.**\n- The AI segment\'s GPU hardware, data centers, and related infrastructure are capitalized and depreciated. Because depreciation is an EBITDA add-back, the cost of building the AI asset base is largely invisible in Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n**Two distortions result:**\n\n1. **Cross-segment distortion.** Comparing Space EBITDA to AI EBITDA is apples-to-oranges: the same economic activity—constructing long-lived productive capacity—reduces Space EBITDA (expensed R&D) but does not reduce AI EBITDA (capitalized, then depreciation added back). This mechanically makes the AI segment appear more profitable on an EBITDA basis than the Space segment, even though both are in heavy investment phases. The Q1 2026 figures illustrate this starkly: Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA was $(351)M while AI was $(609)M, but the gap would look very different if Starship build costs were capitalized like AI compute.\n\n2. **Time-series distortion within Space.** The filing states that once Starship reaches commercialization (delivering payload to orbit), "Starship costs will generally be capitalized and then depreciated in the cost of revenue." At that point, the resulting depreciation will be **excluded** from Segment Adjusted EBITDA. This means Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA will mechanically improve at commercialization—not because economics changed, but because the same cash outflows shift from expensed R&D (in EBITDA) to capitalized depreciation (out of EBITDA). A pre- vs. post-commercialization comparison of Space EBITDA would overstate the improvement in true economic profitability.\n\n---\n\n### Related Consideration (Not One of the Two, but Material)\n\nShare-based compensation is also excluded from Segment Adjusted EBITDA, and its magnitude is highly uneven across segments: AI SBC was $1,063M in 2025 and $378M in Q1 2026 alone, versus $515M (Space) and $369M (Connectivity) for full-year 2025. Because SBC represents a real economic cost (dilution), excluding it flatters the AI segment\'s relative EBITDA more than the other segments. (The filing also notes $60M of SBC was capitalized in Q1 2026, so the total economic cost of equity awards exceeds even the expensed amounts shown in the reconciliations.)\n\n---\n\n### Bottom Line\n\nEBITDA-based segment comparisons are most misleading when (1) segments have materially different capital intensity, useful lives, and depreciation methods (AI\'s $14B of non-depreciating CIP and 20–25 year data centers vs. Connectivity\'s 3–5 year satellite replacement cycle vs. Space\'s units-of-production flight-vehicle depreciation), and (2) the accounting classification of long-lived asset creation differs across segments or over time (Space\'s expensed Starship R&D vs. AI\'s capitalized compute infrastructure, and the impending reclassification of Starship costs upon commercialization). In both situations, Segment Adjusted EBITDA can show a segment as more or less "profitable" than its true economics warrant.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Adjusted EBITDA definition, segment financial information, capital expenditures, depreciation and useful lives, Starship R&D accounting policy, AI compute infrastructure and CIP disclosures, share-based compensation by segment"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
